content.description: Technical slab climb with a boulder start.  Crux is getting to the first bolt. (Old school 5.8). The start is perhaps a bit contrived since the crack is so close, but the rest is fun balancy climbing on decent rock.
content.location: Just left of the obvious double cracks.  Rap rings.

content.description:
This is a sort of interesting feature in the middle of the Corral wall. It's an hourglass looking flake thing. It's attached at the bottom and top but you could wrap your arm around it in the middle. The right side of the flake provides a moderate crack climb. The pro is mostly solid, but I wouldn't want to test it in the middle where the flake is so thin.

The anchors for Green Street can be used to lower off.
Face climb past bolts and horizontal crack, moving left at top to the Haze anchors.
content.location: Face climb to the right of Haze.

content.description: A really fun route with varied technical moves on steep flakes and over a tricky bulge.  Crux is getting to the first bolt - which is pretty high off the ground.  (Stick clip start for some folks.)  The rest is pretty well protected and enjoyable.
content.location: Second bolted route to the right of the obvious double cracks.  Look for an obvious "steering wheel" flake sticking out around the second bolt. Rap off rings.

content.description:
There is a corridor between Double Dome and the Corral Wall. This route is on the left side of the corridor (on Double Dome).

A difficult start on painfully sharp crimps leads to easier friction climbing on lower angle rock. Very short.

This bolted face is just to the right of the Pachyderm flake. Start at a juggy horizontal crack and pull over a bulge on good patina holds. Then up more balancy face climbing on razor sharp patina to stance at a horizontal. Make a highstep onto the slab and friction your way to the top. This route is fairly sustained.

There is a corridor between Double Dome and the Corral Wall. This route is on the right (the far left end of Corral Wall) and immediately across from Grit. This route is a little bit longer than Grit, and a little bit better than Grit.

Big jugs lead up the initial steep section. Then climb up slab which gets a little bit steeper near the end where you'll find a stout 5.7 crux.

The crux is below the anchor.

Lots of positive palm holds.  Granite is still grainy due to it being a newer route.

Good bolt line.

Outstanding views out to the Nevada border and Boundary Peak.
content.location: On the west face of the west dome in the Double Dome/Corral area.
